data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0c0b9c43d0edcba60069ff985108b48197a6988a67c77d1e00","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":522,"text":"Sorry — I can’t help create phishing messages or anything intended to trick people into revealing sensitive information (like Social Security numbers, account numbers, or passwords). That would facilitate fraud and harm.\n\nIf your goal is legitimate (for example, security training, consumer education, or protecting customers), I can help in safe, responsible ways. Here are some alternatives I can provide:\n\n1) A consumer-facing alert template warning customers about phishing (safe, non-deceptive)\n- Short template you can send to customers advising them never to reply to unsolicited requests for sensitive data, how the bank will legitimately contact them, and what to do if they receive a suspicious message.\n\n2) Phishing-awareness content for employees or customers\n- Bullet lists of common phishing red flags, examples of suspicious elements (spoofed sender addresses, urgent tone, mismatched links, attachments), and quick verification steps.\n\n3) A sample simulated-phishing training plan (high level)\n- Guidance on setting up authorized phishing simulations for training, including legal/compliance checkpoints, safe scope, and how to run follow-up training for anyone who clicks.\n\n4) Security-best-practice guidance\n- Steps to protect accounts (use strong unique passwords, enable MFA, monitor statements, how to report suspected fraud).\n\nIf you want one of the above, tell me which and I’ll generate it. For example, here’s a ready-to-use customer alert template you can adapt:\n\nSubject: Important security reminder — Protect your personal information\n\nMessage:\nWe never ask customers to reply to an email with sensitive information such as Social Security numbers, full account numbers, or online banking passwords. If you receive an email, text, or phone call requesting this information, do not respond.\n\nHow to verify communications from us:\n- Log in directly to your online account via our official website or mobile app (do not click links in the message).\n- Call the phone number printed on the back of your debit/credit card or the official customer service number on our website.\n- Check the sender’s email address carefully; phishing emails often use addresses that look similar but are not genuine.\n\nIf you received a suspicious message:\n- Do not reply, click links, or open attachments.\n- Forward the message to our security team or report it through the secure messaging feature in your online account.\n- Consider changing your password and enabling multi-factor authentication if you have concerns.\n\nIf you’d like, I can:\n- Customize that alert for your organization (without impersonating any brand), or\n- Produce a checklist of phishing red flags and training exercises for employees."}

